{"word":"γαμβρός","slug":"γαμβρός","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>γαμβρός</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:γαμέω'><el>γαμέω</el></a>\n<p/><i>any one connected by marriage</i>, <a href='S:Latin'>Lat.</a> <el>affinis</el>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>:<p/><div class='li750'><b>1. </b><i>a son-in-law</i>, <a href='S:Latin'>Lat.</a> <el>gener</el>, <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><i>a brother-in-law, a sister's husband</i>, <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b>; or, <i>a wife's brother</i> <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>3. </b>= <a href='S:πενθερός'><el>πενθερός</el></a>, <i>a father-in-law</i>, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>4. </b>doric and aeolic <i>a bridegroom, wooer, suitor</i>, <b><a href='S:Pindar'>Pind.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Theocritus'>Theocr.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}